<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911209-0031</DOCNO><DOCID>911209-0031.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- National Medical Enterprises Inc.:   Health Care Concern Says   It Will Consolidate Units</HL><DATE>12/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5D</SO><CO>   NME</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   National Medical Enterprises Inc., Santa Monica, Calif.,said it will fold the operations of its Recovery Centers ofAmerica unit into those of its Psychiatric Institutes ofAmerica unit.   The move will reduce overhead costs by an undeterminedamount, said a spokeswoman for National Medical, a healthcare services concern. A handful of corporate management jobswill be eliminated as part of the consolidation, she said.</LP><TEXT>   Recovery Centers of America operates 13 substance abusetreatment centers in nine states and manages 22 other unitsin general hospitals. The free-standing centers will continueto operate under the New Beginnings name, National Medicalsaid.   The consolidation isn't related to federal and stateinvestigations of alleged unethical or illegal activity atthe Psychiatric Institutes of America unit, the spokeswomansaid. Partly because of declining occupancy rates at thepsychiatric hospitals in the wake of the investigations,National Medical recently trimmed its earnings estimates forfiscal 1992.</TEXT></DOC>